Button

Buttons are an essential element of interaction design. Their primary role is to help people take actions quickly.

work in progress
button
buttons
filter chip

Overview

A button serve as an interactive element that enables users to perform an action or make a choice with a simple click or tap. It's important to decide what type of button and what em in order to give the user action highest prioritised. A good rule of thumb is to use only one primary action in each context.

Buttons

We have a group of different buttons used for specific purposes.

1. Normal
2. Icon button
3. Extended FAB
4. Split button
5. Next and back button
6. Category button

Normal button

The normal button is our most used button. Comes in primary, secondary and tertiary. In the sizes small, medium and large.

The normal button can be used as the positive, negative and inverted type.

Normal in primary, secondary and tertiary
Positive and negative button in primary

Icon button

Used for very common actions, because most people will not understand buttons that don't have a label connected. They are often tightly grouped with other components to create context for the buttons purpose.

The Icon button comes in primary, secondary, tertiary. In the sizes small, medium, large. The Icon button also comes as tonal in two sets. One tonal in grey, used mostly on our container colour. And a few custom tonal combinations, used on custom combination cards. Example our alert ribbons.

The icon button can be used as the positive, negative and inverted type also when the context needs it. Comes in primary, secondary, tertiary. In the sizes small, medium, large.

Icon button, normal and positive
Tonal and custom tonal
Tonal custom combinations on Alert ribbon

Floating action button

Only used for functions central to the user experience, such as support and help features that needs to be accessible at all times. The button is always floating visible in the users viewport, typically in the lower right corner. This button can be used with icon only.

Used only as primary.

This is the floating action button.

Split button

Used to group a set of actions that would otherwise be separate buttons and clutter the screen. Clicking the arrow-part will trigger a contextual menu with actionable options.

Comes in both primary and secondary types.

Split button primary

Next and back button

Used inside flows to signal the direction forward or backward.

Back button comes in both primary and secondary state depending on what suits the content. The Next button comes only as primary.

Next button only in primary
Back button primary
Back button secondary

Category button

Used to both signal what or which categories an item belong to, and to work as navigation to see other items belonging to the same category.

Example of two categories

Style

  • Normal : The normal button!
  • Negative : Use for the actions that may be harmful/destructive. A good example is deleting.
  • Positive : Use this for buying stocks/funds etc. Transaction-action.
  • Inverted : Used to place on other than the normal backgrounds (typically darker tones).
  • Tonal : Only used internal in other components
All types of buttons

Hierarchy

It's critical to find the right balance of what buttons to use. It's up to us as designers to guide and inform the users to take the right action.

  • Primary buttons require the most attention from your users.
  • Secondary buttons, as the name says, is the second most likely choice.
  • Tertiary buttons are used for less used or unwanted actions that is still relevant to find.
From top - primary, secondary, tertiary.

Button sizes

The buttons comes in 32, 40 and 48 px.

Primary button with solid container
Secondary button with transparent container and 1 ps border.
Tertiary button with transparent container and no border.

Placements

A general rule is to always strive to place buttons in connection to the items they control. Modals and flows move the user from left to right, therefore the buttons are placed to the right. In overviews and widgets, the user tends to read from top to bottom, therefore the buttons are kept to the left.

Left

  • Place the affirmative/primary button on the left, and the dismissive/secondary button on the right

  • Used on basic/overview pages, widgets or when content is mostly on the left side of the page

Left placement after short survey.

Right

  • Place the affirmative/primary button on the right, the dismissive/secondary button on the left.

  • Used for modals (dialog, slide-out, take-over) and flows (such as wizards)

Right alignment in dialog

In mobile devices

  • If one button, use the full width of the screen (with margins).

  • If two buttons, aim to place them side by side, with 1 rem between them. It is allowed to stack them if needed.

  • If three buttons, consider the need for all of them. "Cancel/close" might be x in the top right corner. Worst case scenario: place the two buttons side by and one link button under.

Side by side in mobile

Do’s and dont’s

Do

  • Use only one primary action in the same context of several actions.

Don’t

  • Use the tonal icon buttons stand-alone, it should only be used inside other components with a toned background.

  • Don't use many buttons of the same kind, make a decision to enforce a hierarchy.

DO
DON'T
